<div id="pf4" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="4"><div class="pc pc4 w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h2 y2 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Introduction </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In this document we will first have a small theory discussion about the main concept behind the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y4 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">implementation of  our system defining what is a parser and the AST structure, followed by a </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y5 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">description about the eager evaluate strategy and a quick description about functor, applicative and </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y6 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">monad in haskell. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y7 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Later we will go much on detail about the grammar of the CSKN language described by BNF </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">notation and we will describe the architecture of the system explaining the single parts. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Finally we will propose some example to try the system and we will explain more in detail some </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ya ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">non trivial implementation of the system.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h2 yb ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> <span class="_ _0"> </span> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 yc ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 yc ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 yc ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 4 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pf5" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="5"><div class="pc pc5 w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 yd w0 h6"><div class="t m0 x1 h2 ye ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Theory background </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 yf ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Parser </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y10 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">A parser is a program that takes a string of characters as input, and produces some form of tree that </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y11 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">makes the syntactic structure of the string explicit. For example, given the string 2*3+4, a parser for </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y12 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">arithmetic expressions might produce a tree of the following form, in which the numbers appear at </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y13 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the leaves of the tree, and the operators appear at the nodes: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y14 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x3 h3 y15 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y16 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y17 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The structure of this tree makes explicit that + and * are operators with two arguments, and that * </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y18 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">has higher priority than +. Parsers are an important topic in computing, because most real-life </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y19 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">programs use a parser to preprocess their input.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Making the structure of the input explicit considerably simplifies its further processing. For </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">example, once a numeric expression has been parsed into a tree structure as in the example above, </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">evaluating the expression is then straightforward. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 y1d ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">An abstract syntax tree (AST), or just syntax tree, is a tree representation of the abstract syntactic </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">structure of source code written in a programming language. Each node of the tree denotes a </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y20 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">construct occurring in the source code. The syntax is &quot;abstract&quot; in the sense that it does not </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y21 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">represent every detail appearing in the real syntax, but rather just the structural, content-related </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y22 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">details. For instance, grouping parentheses are implicit in the tree structure, and a syntactic </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y23 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">construct like an if-condition-then expression may be denoted by means of a single node with three </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y24 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">branches. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y25 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">From now on each we refer to AST we intend the Abstract Syntax Tree produced by the parsing </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y26 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">process. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 y27 ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Eager interpretation </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y28 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">When we have to evaluate arguments to a given function we have two different and opposite </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y29 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">strategy that we can follow: </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y2a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>Call-by-value (<span class="ff4"><span class="ff3">Eager</span></span></div><div class="t m1 x5 h5 y2a ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x5 h3 y2a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">). </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y2b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>Call-by-name (<span class="ff4"><span class="ff3">lazy</span></span></div><div class="t m1 x6 h5 y2b ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x6 h3 y2b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">). </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y2c ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y2c ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y2c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 5 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pf6" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="6"><div class="pc pc6 w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y2d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Give a function, e.g <span class="ff4"><span class="ff3">f(t) ,</span></span></div><div class="t m1 x7 h5 y2d ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x7 h3 y2d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> the eager strategy suggest to evaluate the argument t (that can be a simple </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y2e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">variable or the result of another function) first and once a result is obtained, for example an integer </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y2f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">n, to then proceed with the evaluation of <span class="ff4"><span class="ff3">f</span></span></div><div class="t m1 x8 h5 y2f ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x8 h3 y2f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(n); in the sense that as soon as the argument is read it is </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y30 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">immediately evaluated. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y31 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The lazy strategy (as the name suggest) pass directly to the definition of the function, and if the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y32 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">value of a certain argument t is needed just then the evaluation of the t argument is performed. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y33 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The two choices have vastly different effects. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y34 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">If a certain argument t is frequently use in the definition of the function, a call-by-name strategy </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y35 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">will ri-evaluate each time the argument is needed in the definition, a call-by-value strategy instead </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y36 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">will calculate first all the arguments and then will proceed with the evaluation of the function. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y37 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">On the other hand, if the evaluation of an argument (which may never be used in the function), </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y38 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">leads to a divergence, its divergence can needlessly cause the divergence of the all function. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y39 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In our implementation we have chosen to use an eager approach. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 y3a ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Haskell: Functor, Applicative and Monads </div><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y3b ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">Functors </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In Haskell, functions of type a -&gt; b transform values of type a into values of type b. For example, </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the (+1) :: Int -&gt; Int function increments a number by 1, and the show :: Int -&gt; String turns a number </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">into its string representation. But what if your value was enclosed in some sort of a container? </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">That is the idea behind the functor algebra.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y40 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The class of types that  support such a mapping function are called functors. In Haskell, this concept </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y41 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">is captured by the following class declaration in the standard prelude:  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y42 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y43 w1 h9"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y44 ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">class<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Functor<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> f <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y45 ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">fmap<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> :: (a -&gt; b) -&gt; f a -&gt; f b </span></span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 hb y46 ff7 fs1 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y47 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">That is, for a parameterised type f to be an instance of the class Functor, it must support a function </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y48 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">fmap of the specified type. The intuition is that fmap takes a function of type a -&gt; b and a structure </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y49 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">of type f a whose elements have type a, and applies the function to each such element to give a </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y4a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">structure of type f b whose elements now have type b. The fact that f must be a parameterised type, </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y4b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">that is, a type that takes another type as a parameter, is determined automatically during type </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y4c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">inference by virtue of the application of f to the types a and b in the specified type for fmap in the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y4d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">class declaration. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y4e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">As we would expect, the type of lists can be made into a functor by simply defining fmap to be the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y4f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">function map. Another example can be the built-in type Maybe a that represents values of type a </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y50 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">that may either fail or succeed:  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y51 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y52 w1 hc"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y53 ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">data<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Maybe<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> a = <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Nothing<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> | <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Just<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> a <span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y54 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y55 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">It is straightforward to make the Maybe type into a functor by defining a function fmap of the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y56 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y56 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y56 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 6 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pf7" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="7"><div class="pc pc7 w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y57 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">appropriate type, as follows:  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y58 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y59 w1 hd"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y5a ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">instance<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Functor<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Maybe<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7">  </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y5b ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- fmap :: (a -&gt; b) -&gt; Maybe a -&gt; Maybe b <span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y5c ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">fmap<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> _ <span class="ff6"></span></span></span><span class="fc3">Nothing<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> = <span class="ff6"></span></span></span>Nothing<span class="ff7 fc2">  </span></span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y5d ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">fmap<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> g (<span class="ff6"></span></span></span><span class="fc3">Just<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> x) = <span class="ff6"></span></span></span>Just<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> (g x) </span><span class="ff2"> </span></span></span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y5e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y5f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">That is, mapping a function over a failed value results in the failure being propagated, while for </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y60 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">success we apply the function to the underlying value and retag the result. For example:  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y61 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y62 w1 he"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y63 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">&gt; fmap (+1) Nothing  </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y64 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">Nothing </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y65 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">&gt; fmap (*2) (Just 3) </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y66 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">Just 6 </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y67 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">&gt; fmap not (Just False) </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y68 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">Just True <span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y69 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y6a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Note that in addition to providing a function fmap of the specified type, functors are also required to </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y6b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">satisfy two equational laws: </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y6c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>fmap id = id </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y6d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>fmap (g . h)  =  fmap g . fmap h </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y6e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Where id is the identity and . is the composition of the functions g and h. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y6f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The first equation states that fmap preserves the identity function, in the sense that applying fmap to </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y70 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">this function returns the same function as the result. The second equation above states that fmap </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y71 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">also preserves function composition, in the sense that applying fmap to the composition of two </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y72 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">functions gives the same result as applying fmap to the two functions separately and then </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y73 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">composing. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y74 ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">Applicatives </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y75 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Functors abstract the idea of mapping a function over each element of a structure. Suppose now that </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y76 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">we wish to generalise this idea to allow functions with any number of arguments to be mapped, </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y77 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">rather than being restricted to functions with a single argument. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y78 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In fact the Applicative functor does just that: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y79 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y7a w1 hf"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y7b ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">class<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Functor<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> f =&gt; <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Applicative<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> f <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y7c ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">pure<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> :: a -&gt; f a </span></span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y7d ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">(&lt;*&gt;) :: f (a -&gt; b) -&gt; f a -&gt; f b<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y7e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y7f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">That is, pure converts a value of type a into a structure of type f a, while &lt;*&gt; is a generalised form </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y80 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">of function application for which the argument function, the argument value, and the result value </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y81 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">are all contained in f structures. As with normal function application, the &lt;*&gt; operator is written </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y82 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">between its two arguments and is assumed to associate to the left. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y83 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y84 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y84 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y84 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 7 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pf8" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="8"><div class="pc pc8 w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y85 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Continuing the example from the Functor section, using the fact that Maybe is a functor and hence </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y86 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">supports fmap, it is straightforward to make this type into an applicative functor:  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y87 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y88 w1 he"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y89 ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">instance<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Applicative<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Maybe<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y8a ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- pure :: a -&gt; Maybe a <span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y8b ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">pure<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> = <span class="ff6"></span></span></span><span class="fc3">Just<span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y8c ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- (&lt;*&gt;) :: Maybe (a -&gt; b) -&gt; Maybe a -&gt; Maybe b <span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y8d ff5 fs5 fc3 sc0 ls0 ws0">Nothing<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> &lt;*&gt; _ = <span class="ff6"></span></span></span>Nothing<span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y8e ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">(<span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">Just</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> g) &lt;*&gt; mx = fmap g mx <span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y8f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y90 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">That is, the function pure transforms a value into a successful result, while the operator &lt;*&gt; applies </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y91 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">a function that may fail to an argument that may fail to produce a result that may fail. For example:  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y92 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y93 w1 he"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y94 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">&gt; pure (+1) &lt;*&gt; Just 1  </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y95 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">Just 2 </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y96 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">&gt; pure (+) &lt;*&gt; Just 1 &lt;*&gt; Just 2  </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y97 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">Just 3 </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y98 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">&gt; pure (+) &lt;*&gt; Nothing &lt;*&gt; Just 2  </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y99 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">Nothing<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y9a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y9b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In summary, the applicative style for lists supports a form of non-deterministic programming in </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y9c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">which we can apply pure functions to multi-valued arguments without the need to manage the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y9d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">selection of values or the propagation of failure, as this is taken care of by the applicative </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y9e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">machinery. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y9f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ya0 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In addition to providing the functions pure and &lt;*&gt;, applicative functors are also required to satisfy </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ya1 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">four equational laws: </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 ya2 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>pure id &lt;*&gt; x   = x </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 ya3 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>pure (g x)   = pure g &lt;*&gt; pure x </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 ya4 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>x &lt;*&gt; pure y   =  pure (\g -&gt; g y) &lt;*&gt; x </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 ya5 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>x &lt;*&gt; (y &lt;*&gt; z)  =  (pure (.) &lt;*&gt; x &lt;*&gt; y) &lt;*&gt; z  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ya6 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ya7 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The first equation states that pure preserves the identity function, in the sense that applying pure to </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ya8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">this function gives an applicative version of the identity function. The second equation states that </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ya9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">pure also preserves function application, in the sense that it distributes over normal function </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yaa ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">application to give applicative application. The third equation states that when an effectful function </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yab ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">is applied to a pure argument, the order in which we evaluate the two components doesn’t matter. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yac ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">And finally, the fourth equation states that, modulo the types that are involved, the operator &lt;*&gt; is </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yad ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">associative. It is a useful exercise to work out the types for the variables in each of these laws.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 yae ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 yae ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 yae ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 8 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pf9" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="9"><div class="pc pc9 w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 yd w0 h6"><div class="t m0 x1 h8 yaf ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">Monads </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yb0 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">A Monad wraps a value or a computation with a particular context. A monad must define both a </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yb1 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">means of wrapping normal values in the context, and a way of combining computations within the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yb2 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">context. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yb3 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Just like with functors and applicative functors, Haskell represents monads with a type class. It has </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yb4 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">two functions: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yb5 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 yb6 w1 hd"><div class="t m0 x9 ha yb7 ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">class<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Applicative<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> m =&gt; <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Monad<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> m <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7">  </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha yb8 ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">return<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> :: a -&gt; m a  </span></span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha yb9 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">(&gt;&gt;=) :: m a -&gt; (a -&gt; m b) -&gt; m b </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha yba ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">return<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> = pure </span><span class="ff2"> </span></span></div></div><div class="c x0 yd w0 h6"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ybb ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ybc ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">That is, a monad is an applicative type m that supports return and &gt;&gt;= functions of the specified </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ybd ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">types. The default definition return = pure means that return is normally just another name for the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ybe ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">applicative function pure, but can be overridden in instances declarations if desired. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ybf ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Following the Maybe example, the Maybe Monad is defined in the following way: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yc0 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 yc1 w1 hd"><div class="t m0 x9 ha yc2 ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">instance<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Monad<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Maybe<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7">  </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha yc3 ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- (&gt;&gt;=) :: Maybe a -&gt; (a -&gt; Maybe b) -&gt; Maybe b <span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha yc4 ff5 fs5 fc3 sc0 ls0 ws0">Nothing<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> &gt;&gt;= _ = <span class="ff6"></span></span></span>Nothing<span class="ff7 fc2">  </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha yc5 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">(<span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">Just</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> x) &gt;&gt;= f = f x <span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 yd w0 h6"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yc6 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yc7 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">As defined in the standard prelude, the bind operator for the Maybe type is defined using pattern </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yc8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">matching rather than case analysis for simplicity. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yc9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">As an example we define the function half in the following manner: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yca ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 ycb w1 h10"><div class="t m0 x9 ha ycc ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">half<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> x = <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">if</span></span></span><span class="ff7 fc2"> even x </span></span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha ycd ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">  <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">then</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">Just</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> (x `div` <span class="ff6"></span><span class="fc7">2<span class="ff6"></span></span>) </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha yce ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">  <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">else</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> <span class="ff6"><span fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Since Maybe is a Monad we can do the following with the half function: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yd1 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 yd2 w1 h9"><div class="t m0 x9 ha yd3 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">&gt; Just 20 &gt;&gt;= half &gt;&gt;= half &gt;&gt;= half </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha yd4 ff7 fs5 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">Nothing<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 yd w0 h6"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yd5 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yd6 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Haskell also provides us with some syntactical sugar for monads, called do notation. For example </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yd7 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">using the IO Monad we can chain functions with the &gt;&gt;= or do notation: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yd8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 yd9 w1 hc"><div class="t m0 x9 ha yda ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">getLine<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> &gt;&gt;= readFile &gt;&gt;= putStrLn</span><span class="ff2"> </span></span></div></div><div class="c x0 yd w0 h6"><div class="t m0 x1 h11 ydb ff2 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 ydc w1 hc"><div class="t m0 x9 ha ydd ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">foo<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> = <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">do</span></span> </span></span></div></div><div class="c x0 yd w0 h6"><div class="t m0 x1 h4 yde ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 yde ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 yde ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 9 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pfa" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="a"><div class="pc pca w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x1 ydf w1 h10"><div class="t m0 x9 ha ye0 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0"> filename &lt;- getLine </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha ye1 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0"> contents &lt;- readFile filename </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha ye2 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0"> putStrLn contents<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 yd w0 h6"><div class="t m0 x1 h11 ye3 ff2 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ye4 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In a similar manner to functors and applicatives, the two monadic primitives are required to satisfy </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ye5 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">some equational laws: </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 ye6 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>return x &gt;&gt;= f   =  f x </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 ye7 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>mx &gt;&gt;= return  =  mx </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 ye8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">-<span class="_ _1"> </span>(mx &gt;&gt;= f) &gt;&gt;= g  =  mx &gt;&gt;= (\x -&gt; (f x &gt;&gt;= g)) </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 ye9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The first equation states that if we return a value and then feed this into a monadic function, this </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yea ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">should give the same result as simply applying the function to the value. Dually, the second </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yeb ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">equation states that if we feed the result of a monadic computation into the function return, this </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yec ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">should give the same result as simply performing the computation. Together, these two equations </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yed ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">state, modulo the fact that the second argument to &gt;&gt;= involves a binding operation, that return is </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yee ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the identity for the &gt;&gt;= operator. The third equation concerns the link between &gt;&gt;= and itself, and </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yef ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">expresses (again modulo binding) that &gt;&gt;= is associative.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yf0 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yf1 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yf2 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yf3 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h2 yf4 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> <span class="_ _0"> </span> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 yf5 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 yf5 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 yf5 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 10 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pfb" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="b"><div class="pc pcb w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h2 yf6 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">CSKN Language </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 yf7 ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Language description </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yf8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The CSKN language is an eager imperative programming language composed by few commonly </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yf9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">used commands.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 yfa ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Specifically : </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 yfb ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">Sequencing<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: executes statements in sequence; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 yfc ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">Assignment<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: instruction that assign a value to a variable that is calculated if it is written by </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xa h3 yfd ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">an expression; </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 yfe ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">Conditional<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: control structure if-then like; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 yff ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">While-loop<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: iterative control structure while-do like; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y100 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y101 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">CSKN is a language that accept Boolean and Integer values and can evaluate the following type of </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y102 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">arithmetic expressions: </div><div class="t m0 x4 h12 y103 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">Number<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: Any n <span class="ffa">∊</span> <span class="ffa">ℤ</span>; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y104 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">Location<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: content of a variable; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y105 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">Sum, Subtraction, Product, Division<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: canonical arithmetical operations with division that </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y106 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">returns the quotient of the operation; </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y107 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">and boolean expressions: </div><div class="t m0 x4 h12 y108 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">Boolean<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: b <span class="ffa">∊</span> {True, False}; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y109 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">Location<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: content of a variable; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y10a ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">And, Or, Not<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: canonical logic operations; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y10b ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff1">&lt;, &lt;=, &gt;, &gt;=, ==, /=<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">: canonical interpretation of these operators, compares two arithmetic </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y10c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">expression and returns a boolean value.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y10d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y10e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 y10f ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> <span class="_ _3"> </span> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y110 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y110 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y110 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 11 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pfc" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="c"><div class="pc pcc w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h7 y111 ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">BNF Grammar </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y112 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Our interpreter will accept string belonging to the language define by the following grammar.   </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y113 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">We define our grammar using BNF notation<span class="ff4"></span><span class="fc2">. </span></div><div class="t m0 x1 h13 y114 ff1 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 xb h14 y115 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c xc y116 w2 h15"><div class="t m0 xd h3 y117 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;program&gt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2"> ::= {&lt;sqnc&gt;} </span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y118 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;sqnc&gt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2"> ::= &lt;stm&gt;; &lt;sqnc&gt; </span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">  &lt;stm&gt;; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y119 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;stm&gt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2"> ::=  &lt;command&gt; </span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;expr&gt;</span></span></span> </div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y11a ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;comm&gt; <span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">::= &lt;identifier&gt; = &lt;expr&gt; </span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> IF [&lt;bexpr&gt;] &lt;program&gt;  </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y11b ff2 fs6 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">            | <span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">WHILE [&lt;bexpr&gt;] &lt;program&gt; </span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y11c ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;expr&gt; <span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">::=  &lt;bexpr&gt; </span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;aexpr&gt;</span></span></span> </div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y11d ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;aexpr&gt; <span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">::=  &lt;aterm&gt; </span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;aterm&gt; + &lt;aexpr&gt; </span></span><span class="ff2 fs6">| <span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">&lt;aterm&gt; - &lt;aexpr&gt; </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y11e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff1">bexpr</span></span>&gt; ::=  &lt;bterm&gt; <span class="ff4"></span><span class="fs6">| <span class="ffb"></span></span>&lt;bterm&gt; AND &lt;bexpr&gt; <span class="ff4"></span><span class="fs6">| <span class="ffb"></span></span>&lt;bterm&gt; OR &lt;bexpr&gt; </div><div class="t m0 xe h16 y11f ff2 fs6 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;bterm&gt; GREATER &lt;aexpr&gt; | &lt;bterm&gt; GREATER_EQUAL &lt;aexpr&gt;  </span></div><div class="t m0 xe h16 y120 ff2 fs6 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;bterm&gt; LESS &lt;aexpr&gt; <span class="ff4"></span></span>| <span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">&lt;bterm&gt; LESS_EQUAL &lt;aexpr&gt;  </span></div><div class="t m0 xe h16 y121 ff2 fs6 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;bterm&gt; EQUAL &lt;aexpr&gt; <span class="ff4"></span></span>| <span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">&lt;bterm&gt; NOT_EQUAL &lt;aexpr&gt; </span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y122 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;aterm&gt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2"> ::=  &lt;afactor&gt; </span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;afactor&gt; * &lt;aterm&gt;  </span></span><span class="ff2 fs6">| <span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">&lt;afactor&gt; / &lt;aterm&gt;  </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y123 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;afactor&gt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2"> ::=  ( &lt;aexpr&gt; ) </span><span class="ff2 fs6">| <span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">+ &lt;afactor&gt; </span></span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> - &lt;afactor&gt; </span></span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;identifier&gt; </span></span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> &lt;natural&gt;  </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y124 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff1">bterm</span></span>&gt; ::=  ( &lt;bexpr&gt; ) <span class="ff4"></span><span class="fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span></span> NOT &lt;bterm&gt; <span class="ff4"></span><span class="fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span></span> &lt;identifier&gt; <span class="ff4"></span><span class="fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span></span> &lt;bool_val&gt; <span class="ff4"></span><span class="fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span></span> &lt;aexpr&gt; </div><div class="t m0 xf h14 y125 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 xb h14 y126 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y127 ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0"> <span class="_ _4"> </span> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y128 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y128 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y128 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 12 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pfd" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="d"><div class="pc pcd w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y129 ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">Terminals<span class="ff1"> </span></div></div><div class="c xc y12a w2 h17"><div class="t m0 xd h16 y12b ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;natural&gt; ::=<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2">  0 </span><span class="ff2 fs6">| <span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">1 </span></span><span class="ff2 fs6">| <span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1">2 </span></span><span class="ff2 fs7">...<span class="ff1"> </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h16 y12c ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;bool_val&gt; ::=<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2"> TRUE </span><span class="ff2 fs6">|<span class="ffb"></span><span class="fs1"> FALSE  </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h4 y12d ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;identifier&gt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff3"> </span></span></div><div class="t m1 x10 h5 y12d ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x10 h3 y12d ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">::=<span class="ff4"><span class="ff2"> A lower case alphabetic character followed by any alphanumeric string </span></span></div><div class="t m0 xd h3 y12e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">(with     no space in between). </div><div class="t m0 xf h14 y12f ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 xb h14 y130 ff1 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y131 ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">Program, sequence and statement </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y132 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff2">The program node &lt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff1">program&gt; </span></span>is the root of the tree, is objective is simply bound the </span></div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y133 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">program between the two braces. </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y134 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff2">The sequence node &lt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff1">sqnc</span></span>&gt; split each input in statements ( &lt;stm&gt; ) which ends with a </span></div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y135 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">semicolon.  </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y136 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff2">The statement node &lt;<span class="ff4"><span class="ff1">stm</span></span>&gt; is used to produce a command or an expression. </span></div><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y137 ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">Commands </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y138 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The objective of command is to produce the two control structure if and while and give the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y139 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">possibility to assign a specific expression to an identifier. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y13a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">More precisely the if control structure is composed by the keyword IF, an expression &lt;expr&gt; </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y13b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">enclose between square brackets and  a program &lt;program&gt;; the while structure is similar to the IF </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y13c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">structure but it’s repeat the statements while the condition is true as the canonical definition. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y13d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y13e ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">Expressions: Arithmetic and Boolean </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y13f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Expression &lt;expr&gt; can be an arithmetic expression &lt;aexpr&gt; or a boolean expression &lt;bexpr&gt;: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y140 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y141 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff2">arithmetic expressions: aexpr </span></div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y142 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">An additive expression that starts with an &lt;aterm&gt; followed by either plus or minus, followed </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y143 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">by another &lt;aexpr&gt;. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y144 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">This is a typical recursive definition for parsing expressions of the type &lt;aterm&gt; + &lt;aterm&gt; - </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y145 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;aterm&gt; ... etc.. Example: x - 5 + y. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y146 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">A lonely &lt;aterm&gt; is also considered an &lt;aexpr&gt;, e.g  44. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y147 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;aterms&gt; are more tightly bound than &lt;aexpr&gt;, corresponding to higher precedence of </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y148 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">multiplicative vs. additive operators.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y149 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y149 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y149 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 13 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pfe" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="e"><div class="pc pce w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 xb h3 y14a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">We&apos;ll consider two forms or terms: &lt;afactor&gt; followed by a multiplication or division sign, </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y14b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">followed by another &lt;aterm&gt;. This production corresponds to terms of the form &lt;afactor&gt; * </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y14c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;afactor&gt; / &lt;afactor&gt; .... Example: 2 * x /2. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y14d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">An &lt;aterm&gt; could also be a lonely &lt;afactor&gt;. Example: 44. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y14e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Finally, the most tightly bound production is that of the &lt;afactor&gt;, which can be one of: </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y14f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">A &lt;natural&gt;, like 147; an &lt;identifier&gt; (variable name), like x11; a unary plus or minus in front </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y150 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">of an &lt;afactor&gt;, like -x or +12; a parenthesized &lt;aexpr&gt;, like (a + b/2). </div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y151 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y152 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff2">boolean expressions: bexpr </span></div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y153 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">A boolean expression that starts with a &lt;bterm&gt; followed by either AND or OR logical </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y154 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">operations, followed by another &lt;bexpr&gt;. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y155 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">So it is possible the recursive definition for parsing expressions of the type &lt;bterm&gt; AND </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y156 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;bterm&gt; - &lt;bterm&gt; ... etc.. Example: x AND TRUE OR y. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y157 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">A lonely &lt;bterm&gt; is also considered an &lt;bexpr&gt;. Example: FALSE. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y158 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">A &lt;bexpr&gt; can be also composed by a &lt;bterm&gt; follower by the operators GREATER, </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y159 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">GREATER_EQUAL, LESS, LESS_EQUAL, EQUAL, NOT_EQUAL and an &lt;aexpr&gt;. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y15a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">This makes it possible to define comparisons between arithmetic expressions like 4+5 </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y15b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">GREATER 6-5. </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y15c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;bterms&gt; are of the type: &lt;aexpr&gt; for  confronting an &lt;aexpr&gt; with another; a &lt;bool_val&gt;, like </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y15d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">TRUE or FALSE; an &lt;identifier&gt; (variable name), like b1; a unary NOT operator in front of a </div><div class="t m0 xb h3 y15e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&lt;bterm&gt;, like NOT x or NOT TRUE; a parenthesized &lt;bexpr&gt;, like (a AND NOT b2).<span class="fs5"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x1 h11 y15f ff2 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y160 ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h2 y161 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> <span class="_ _0"> </span> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y162 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y162 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y162 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 14 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pff" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="f"><div class="pc pcf w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h2 y163 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Design </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 y164 ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Architecture </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y165 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The interpreter for the CSKN language has two main modules: </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y166 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff2">The Parser, creates the AST structure from the program input string; </span></div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y167 ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff2">The Evaluator, evaluates expressions, execute commands modifying the memory. </span></div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y168 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y169 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y16a ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 y16b ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Parsing </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y16c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The parser is the component in charge to compute the input program string and recursively builds </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y16d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the AST structure that makes the syntactic structure of the string explicit and permits to finally </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y16e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">evaluate the program. We note that for the implementation of the system we choose to use a parser </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y16f ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">type monadic strategy. That is we make the parser type into an instance of the functor, applicative </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y170 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">and monad classes, in order that the do notation can then be used to combine parsers in sequence. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y171 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In addition we make the parser type into an instance of Alternative to apply one parser to the input </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y172 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">string, and if this fails to then apply another to the same input instead. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y173 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">After parsing a string for a program written in CSKN, we’ll have as a result an AST that makes </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y174 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">explicit how to evaluate the program. <span class="_ _5"> </span> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y175 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y175 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y175 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 15 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pf10" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="10"><div class="pc pc10 w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y176 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">For example a program {a=3+4;} will result in: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y177 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y178 w1 h18"><div class="t m0 x9 h19 y179 ff7 fs8 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">parse program <span class="ffc"></span><span class="fc8">&quot;{a=3+4;}&quot;</span> </div><div class="t m0 x9 h19 y17a ff7 fs8 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">&gt;[(SeqNode [StatementNode (AssignNode <span class="ffc"></span><span class="fc8">&quot;a&quot;<span class="ffc"></span></span> (SumNode Plus (NumNode 3) (NumNode 4)))],<span class="ffc"></span><span class="fc8">&quot;&quot;<span class="ffc"></span></span>)]<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y17b ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y17c ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The result can be easily viewed as the tree: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y17d ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x11 h3 y17e ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h7 y17f ff1 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Evaluation </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y180 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">For simplicity and for the purposes of this activity it was preferred to use an Eager evaluation </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y181 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">strategy, often used for imperative languages. In other words, the interpreter realized will evaluate </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y182 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the expressions to be associated with the variables as soon as the relative assignment statement is </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y183 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">scanned.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y184 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">For the implementation of this part we use a composition of monads, functor and applicative, </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y185 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">similarly to the parser implementation. Further details are discussed after. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y186 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Another notable design choice is the implementation of a custom type recognized by the language </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y187 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">called Value. The motivation is to simplify the memory implementation and the evaluation process; </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y188 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">more details are discussed in the implementation part. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y189 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y189 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y189 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 16 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>

b) -&gt; Parser a -&gt; Parser b<span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1c4 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">  fmap f p = <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">P</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> $ \inp -&gt; </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1c5 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">    <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">case</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> parse p inp <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">of</span></span> </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1c6 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">      []         -&gt; [] </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1c7 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">      [(v, out)] -&gt; [(f v, out)]<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1c8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1c9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">That is, fmap applies a function to the result value of a parser if the parser succeeds, and propagates </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1ca ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the failure otherwise (failure is the [] empty list).  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1cb ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1cc ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The Parser type can then be made into an applicative functor as follows: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1cd ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y1ce w1 h1e"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1cf ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">instance<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Applicative<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Parser<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7">  </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1d0 ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- pure :: a -&gt; Parser a<span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1d1 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">  pure v = <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">P</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> $ \inp -&gt; [(v, inp)] </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1d2 ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- &lt;*&gt; :: Parser (a -&gt; b) -&gt; Parser a -&gt; Parser b<span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1d3 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">  pf &lt;*&gt; px = <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">P</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> $ \inp -&gt; </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1d4 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">    <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">case</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> parse pf inp <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">of</span></span> </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1d5 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">      []         -&gt; [] </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1d6 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">      [(f, out)] -&gt; parse (fmap f px) out<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1d7 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1d8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Finally, we make the Parser type into a monad: </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1d9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y1da w1 he"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1db ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">instance<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Monad<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Parser<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1dc ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- (&gt;&gt;=) :: Parser a -&gt; (a -&gt; Parser b) -&gt; Parser b<span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1dd ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">  p &gt;&gt;= f = <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">P</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> $ \inp -&gt; </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1de ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">    <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">case</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> parse p inp <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">of</span></span> </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1df ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">      []         -&gt; [] </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1e0 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">      [(v, out)] -&gt; parse (f v) out<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e1 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e2 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">That is, the parser p &gt;&gt;= f fails if the application of the parser p to the input string inp fails, and </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e3 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">otherwise applies the function f to the result value v to give another parser f v, which is then applied </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e4 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">to the output string out that was produced by the first parser to give the final result. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h4 y1e5 ff3 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">             </div><div class="t m1 x2 h5 y1e5 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x2 h3 y1e5 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> 18 </div></div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
<div id="pf13" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="13"><div class="pc pc13 w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w0 h0" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e6 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Because we made Parser as a monadic type, the do notation can be used to sequence parsers and </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e7 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">process their result values. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e8 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1e9 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Another natural way of combining parsers is to apply one parser to the input string, and if this fails </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1ea ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">to then apply another to the same input instead.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1eb ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">We now consider how such a choice operator can be defined for parsers. That is, for an applicative </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1ec ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">functor to be an instance of the Alternative class, it must support empty and &lt;|&gt; primitives of the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1ed ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">specified types:  empty represents an alternative that has failed, and &lt;|&gt; is an appropriate choice </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1ee ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">operator for the type. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1ef ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y1f0 w1 h1e"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1f1 ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">instance<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Alternative<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Parser<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span>where<span class="ff7">  </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1f2 ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- empty :: Parser a<span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1f3 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">  empty = <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">P</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> $ \inp -&gt; [] </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1f4 ff8 fs5 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">-- (&lt;|&gt;) :: Parser a -&gt; Parser a -&gt; Parser a<span class="ff7 fc2"> </span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1f5 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">  p &lt;|&gt; q = <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5 fc3">P</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> $ \inp -&gt; </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1f6 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">    <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">case</span><span class="fc0"></span></span> parse p inp <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">of</span></span> </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1f7 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">      []         -&gt; parse q inp </div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y1f8 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">      [(v, out)] -&gt; [(v, out)]<span class="ff2 fc0"> </span></div></div><div class="c x0 y1 w0 h1"><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y1f9 ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x1 h8 y1fa ff2 fs4 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">Basic Parsers </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1fb ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Note: primitive parser from this section are based on the ones explained in the book ”Programming </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1fc ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">in haskell” </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y1fd ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m0 x4 h3 y1fe ff9 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">●<span class="_ _2"> </span><span class="ff2">Item </span></div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y1ff ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">first parsing primitive is called item, which fails if the input string is empty, and succeeds </div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y200 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">with the first character as the result value otherwise:  </div><div class="t m0 xa h3 y201 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x12 y202 w3 h1f"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y203 ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">item<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> :: <span class="ff6"></span></span></span><span class="fc3">Parser<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> <span class="ff6"></span></span></span>Char<span class="ff7 fc2">  </span></span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y204 ff5 fs5 fc4 sc0 ls0 ws0">item<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> = <span class="ff6"></span></span></span><span class="fc3">P<span class="ff6 fc0"><span class="ff7 fc2"> (\inp -&gt; <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">case</span></span></span><span class="ff7 fc2"> inp <span class="ff6"><span class="ff5">of</span></span> </span></span></span></div><div class="t m0 x9 ha y205 ff7 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">[] -&gt; that are candidates for being captured by a monadic structure: the passing </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3cd ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">around and updating of the store, aborting running the program when a run-time error is </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3ce ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">encountered. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3cf ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The first effect is typically captured by a state monad, the second by an error monad. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3d0 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">We used monad transformers to construct a composite monad for our two effects by combining a </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3d1 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">basic state monad and a basic error monad.  </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3d2 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div></div><div class="c x1 y3d3 w1 h1e"><div class="t m0 x9 ha y3d4 ff5 fs5 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">newtype<span class="ff6 fc0"></span><span class="ff7"> <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Interp<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> a = <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Interp<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> { <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">runInterp<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> :: <span class="ff6"></span></span><span class="fc3">Store<span class="ff6 fc0"></span></span><span class="ff7"> -&gt; class="t m1 x17 h5 y3e0 ff4 fs2 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m0 x17 h3 y3e0 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">function is the main function of the evaluation process. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3e1 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Given an AST it executes the commands which modify the working memory that stores the results </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3e2 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">of evaluations. </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3e3 ff2 fs1 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Execution of commands is done in this function, while the evaluation of expressions happens in the </div><div class="t m0 x1 h3 y3e4 ff2 fs1
